  "experiments_summary": "The study investigates the optimization landscape for recovering crystal structures from powder X-ray diffraction (XRD) patterns using gradient descent. Ten structures from the MP20 dataset spanning common space groups were selected. For each structure, 50 distorted versions were generated using two physically motivated noise models: (1) lattice noise via random strain tensors applied to lattice matrices while keeping fractional coordinates fixed, with noise levels σl controlling uniform expansion/compression and shear; (2) coordinate noise via independent Gaussian perturbations to fractional atomic positions with noise scale σc. Distorted structures were optimized using StructSnap, a differentiable XRD simulator, by minimizing three loss functions: negative cosine similarity, MSE, and negative entropy similarity between simulated and ground-truth XRD patterns. Optimization was performed either with or without symmetry constraints, where constrained optimization used projected gradient descent to enforce the correct crystal family at each step. Recovery performance was assessed using Match Rate (fraction of structures matching ground truth via StructureMatcher with tolerances: ltol=0.1, stol=0.2, angle_tol=5°). The optimization landscape was visualized through 2D cross-sections by perturbing pairs of lattice parameters and computing loss contours. For comparison, energy-based relaxation was performed using the CHGNet universal machine learning interatomic potential. XRD patterns were computed using the kinematic scattering model with Pseudo-Voigt peak profiles (η=0.1) and Caglioti parameters (U=0.1, V=0.01, W=0.1), discretized into 0.01° bins over 2θ∈[0°,90°]."
